urgs]]\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Latvian Higher League seasons}}\n{{2012\u201313 in European football (UEFA)}}\n{{2013\u201314 in European football (UEFA)}}\n\n[[Category:Latvian Higher League seasons]]\n[[Category:2013 in Latvian football|1]]\n[[Category:2013\u201314 in European association football leagues|Latvia]]\n[[Category:2012\u201313 in European association football leagues|Latvia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox football league season\n| competition      = [[Latvian Higher League]]\n| season           = 2013\n| winners          = \n| relegated        = \n| continentalcup1  = [[2014\u201315 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = \n| continentalcup2  = [[2014\u201315 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]\n| continentalcup2 qualifiers = \n| continentalcup3  = [[2014\u201315 Baltic League|Baltic League]]\n| continentalcup3 qualifiers = \n| matches          = 135\n| total goals      = 392\n| league topscorer = [[Art\u016brs Kara\u0161ausks]] <br/> [[Andrejs Kova\u013covs]]<br/> (16 goals)\n| biggest home win = [[FK Daugava (2003)|FK Daugava]] 7-1 [[Il\u016bkstes NSS]]\n| biggest away win = [[Il\u016bkstes NSS]] 2-10 [[FK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs|SK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs]]\n| highest scoring  = [[Il\u016bkstes NSS]] 2-10 [[FK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs|SK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs]]\n| longest wins     = [[FK Ventspils]], [[Skonto FC]] (6)\n| longest unbeaten = [[Skonto FC]] (26)\n| longest winless  = \n| longest losses   = [[Il\u016bkstes NSS]] (7)\n| prevseason       = [[2012 Latvian Higher League|2012]]\n| nextseason       = [[2014 Latvian Higher League|2014]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2013 [[Latvian Higher League]]''' was the 22nd season of top-tier [[association football|football]] in [[Latvia]]. [[FC Daugava]] were the defending champions. The season started on 29 March 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://futbolavirsliga.lv/index.php/jaunumi/1257-virsligas-2013-gada-sezona-saksies-29-marta|title=Virsl\u012bgas 2013.gada sezona s\u0101ksies 29.mart\u0101|publisher=Futbolavirsliga.lv|language=Latvian|accessdate=March 3, 2013|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6DWwwItl8?url=http://futbolavirsliga.lv/index.php/jaunumi/1257-virsligas-2013-gada-sezona-saksies-29-marta|archive-date=2013-01-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe league comprised ten teams. The champions of this season were [[FK Ventspils]], followed by [[Skonto FC]]\n\n==Teams==\nThe league had a ten-team circuit like the [[2012 Latvian Higher League|2012 season]].\n2012 [[Latvian First League]] champions [[Il\u016bkstes NSS]] from [[Il\u016bkste]] were directly promoted.\n\n[[FK Daugava (2003)|FK Daugava R\u012bga]] finished the 2012 season in ninth place and were therefore required to compete in a two-legged promotion/relegation play-off against First Division runners-up [[BFC Daugava]]. FK Daugava Riga won the play-off 4\u20131 on aggregate and therefore stayed in the Higher League.\n\n===Stadiums and locations===\n{{Location map+|Latvia|float=right|width=400|caption=Location of teams in the '''2013 Latvian Higher League'''|places=\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=57.416667|long=21.533333|label=[[FK Ventspils|Ventspils]]}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=55.977778|long=26.2975|label=[[Il\u016bkstes NSS]]|position=left}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=56.966667|long=24.133333|label=[[FK Daugava (2003)|Daugava Riga]]<br />[[FS METTA/Latvijas Universit\u0101te|FS METTA]]<br />[[Skonto FC|Skonto]]}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=56.516667|long=21|label=[[FK Liep\u0101jas Metalurgs|Metalurgs]]}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=56.966667|long=23.75|label=[[FC J\u016brmala|J\u016brmala]]<br />[[FK Spartaks J\u016brmala|Spartaks]]|position=left}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=56.58|long=23.716667|label=[[FK Jelgava|Jelgava]]|position=bottom}}\n{{Location map~|Latvia|lat=55.883333|long=26.533333|label=[[FC Daugava|Daugava]]|position=right}}\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Club\n! Location\n! Stadium\n! Capacity\n|-\n|[[File:Flag of Daugavpils.svg|b